content.description: A thin roof crack leads into a left-leaning finger crack. Traverse left and join Boots or exit right to the top.  The bottom of this route is often wet. Named after an amusement part ride.

This route was first climbed back in the 1970’s or perhaps 1960’s given the condition of the bolts ( a short bolt ladder -  ¼”  hard to see relics of the past) back in the early/mid 1980’s.  The crux is a painful pinky jam combined with along reach to a fin shaped section of rock.  Kind of a one move wonder but still really fun.
Shallow left facing corner usually very dirty.
content.location: Between the main wall and the tower.

climbs.name: Post Wired Movement
climbs.fa: FA: Unknown FLA after bolting Leland Windham & Eric Ellis; July 1998

content.description: "Begin on "Kill Me..." then exit left into a seam after the fourth bolt."
content.protection: 6 bolts + medium nut & 2.5" cam. Chain anchors.
content.location: Middle of the formation when you've exited the wildlife tunnel. To the right of the roof with the finger crack, look for the bolt line that splits after the 4th bolt- stay left after the 4th clip and continue up to an independent anchor.

content.description: On the left side of the crag around the corner is this obvious crack.  Pad up the slab past one old bolt and climb the short slabby crack above.  Good mix of hands then fingers for a few moves before reaching a two bolt anchor on the forested ledge. Easily top-roped by walking around.
content.protection: One bolt, 2-4 small-medium size cams or stoppers.

content.description: Off balance laybacking leads to the right side of a roof.  From there easier climbing finishes the route as it rejoins "Flight to Mars" after the 4th bolt (moving right).

climbs.name: Kill Me If I Start To Live
climbs.fa: FA: Unknown.  FLA after bolting Leland Windham

content.description:
"Start on the left side of the main wall below a roof at a bolt. Layback up zigzag flakes and delicate face moves to the top". Stay right when the bolt line splits after the first four clips (going left is "Post Wired Movement, 5.11c").

Quite a few friction slab moves mixed in and fairly pumpy, even on top-rope.

There are two sets of chain anchors- as of March '20. The lower ones are rusty and need removing; use the shiny new set about a foot higher.
content.protection: 9 bolts + 2 sets of chain anchors at the top.
content.location: Pretty much right in front of you after exiting the wildlife tunnel. Look for the roof with the fingercrack and it's the bolt line just to the right.

content.description: Start up the right side of a roof.  Climb past some flexible flakes to a mantle.  From there one hard move leads to easier but most certainly very dirty climbing to the top.  Named after an amusement park ride.
content.protection: Small gear if done ground up.
content.location: Start just right of the Mystical Garden.

content.description: Slap and crimp your way up the bolted face on the detatched pillar. A fun but tricky route with delicate climbing.
content.protection: 4 bolts and 2 bolts at the top for an anchor.
content.location: When you walk into Fun Forest from the wildlife tunnel, look right and you'll see the detached pillar. This route is on the face of it, NOT in the chimney.

content.description: Move up and right from Flight To Mars.  5.10 climbing with poor pro ends at a stance.  From there move to clip a bolt, crank the move and then join Flight To Mars to the top.
Stem or otherwise span the gap between the tower and the main wall.

Start up left avoiding the thin finger crack (5.10) and traverse over to the crack by the tree. Avoid the tree and continue up the corner groove to the bulge at the top.  The crack is sometimes clogged with leaves so a nut tool can be helpful for cleaning out placements or a jam or two.
content.location: Around the left side of the crag. Look for the obvious finger crack.
